04352nam a22005415i 9780520943506DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209435067 a10.1525/97805209435062doi  a(DE-B1597)648533  a(OCoLC)961876782  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0030002bisacsh1 aSmith, Joanna H, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt of Doing Good :bCharity in Late Ming China /cJoanna H Smith; ed. by Joanna Handlin Smith. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (424 p.) :b5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tConventions, Measurements, and Dynasties -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: New Routines: Associations for Doing Good -- t1. Societies For Liberating Animals -- t2. Early Benevolent Societies And Their Visionary Leaders -- t3. The Benevolent Society Among Its Alternatives -- t4. Lectures For The Poor – and the Rich -- t5. A Benevolent Society Viewed from the Margins -- tPart II: Enacting Charitable Routines During a Crisis -- t6. Mobilizing Food Relief -- t7. Aligning With Officials -- t8. Medical Relief and Other Good Deeds -- t9. Beliefs in Charity – and the Rhetoric of Beliefs -- tConclusion: From Moral Transformation toward the Legitimation of Wealth -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn unprecedented passion for saving lives swept through late Ming society, giving rise to charitable institutions that transcended family, class, and religious boundaries. Analyzing lecture transcripts, administrative guidelines, didactic tales, and diaries, Joanna Handlin Smith abandons the facile explanation that charity was a response to poverty and social unrest and examines the social and economic changes that stimulated the fervor for doing good. With an eye for telling details and a finesse in weaving the voices of her subjects into her narrative, Smith brings to life the hard choices that five men faced when deciding whom to help, how to organize charitable distributions, and how to balance their communities' needs against the interests of family and self. She thus shifts attention from tired questions about whether the Chinese had a tradition of charity (they did) to analyzing the nature of charity itself. Skillfully organized and engaging, The Art of Doing Good moves from discussions about moral leadership and beliefs to scrutiny of the daily operation of soup kitchens and medical dispensaries, and from examining local society to generalizing about the just use of resources and the role of social networks in charitable giving. Smith's work will transform our thinking about the boundaries between social classes in late imperial China and about charity in general.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsia. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aHandlin Smith, Joanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025363640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094350640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943506/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles